// @raw117_exempt
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// stdlib/flame/ag_extract.hexa — flame autograd-auto Sub-Deliverable 5
// (RFC 043, scoping note inbox/notes/2026-05-20-flame-autograd-auto-scoping.md
//  §4 "SD5 (open question, NOT pre-committed): true AST-driven derivation
//  from a hexa-lang `fn`'s source — requires compiler hook")
//
// PURPOSE — FIRST STEP of true AST-driven reverse-mode AD. SD1–SD4 are
// manually-keyed rule registries: a human encodes each bwd by hand and
// the registry only stores presence. SD5 demonstrates the genuine
// source-to-source transform shape — ingest a forward primitive as a
// tiny AST, perform a reverse-mode walk over the AST, and emit a
// backward primitive whose closed-form vjp is derived automatically
// from the forward shape (no human writes the bwd body).
//
// SCOPE (g3 — what this file IS and IS NOT):
//   IS  : a minimum-viable AST walker that handles ONE pattern —
//         elementwise unary `relu(x) = if x > 0 then x else 0`. The
//         AST is built in-source (no parser dependency); the walker
//         knows the four node kinds needed for relu (Param, Const,
//         BinOp_GT, IfElse). The emitted bwd is `dx = if x > 0 then
//         dy else 0`, derived purely from the reverse-mode rules for
//         If and >.
//   IS  : self-contained. Does NOT import compiler/parse/ast.hexa
//         (which would pull in the lexer + parser + diag — heavy,
//         out-of-scope for a single-cycle SD). The honest stop-
//         condition in the scoping note §3 reads "If neither is
//         feasible, SD1 collapses to manually-keyed rule registry"
//         — SD5 takes the dual stance for a different reason: AST
//         is feasible standalone, parser dep is the structural
//         blocker. Filed as a future-cycle item — see §"Future
//         work" at bottom.
//   IS  : verified by byte-eq vs a hand-written relu_bwd reference
//         on a fixed-seed input — F-RFC043-AUTOGRAD-AUTO-SD5-RELU-
//         BYTE-EQ. Same closed-form pattern as SD3 (the math IS the
//         hand-written reference; SD5 proves the AST→walk→emit
//         pipeline produces a body that runs identical IEEE-754
//         scalars).
//   NOT : full reverse-mode AD over arbitrary hexa-lang functions.
//         No matmul, no reductions, no compound bodies — those
//         require AST kinds + reverse rules SD5 does not encode.
//         SD5 = pipeline shape, one op.
//   NOT : a re-emit-and-recompile cycle. The emitted bwd source is
//         printed (for inspection / future filing as a generated
//         file) but ALSO interpreted directly inside the test
//         (driver tree-walks the bwd AST). Why: stage0 has no
//         in-process compile-and-load. The interpret path lets the
//         SD5 oracle assert byte-eq without a second hexa
//         invocation — same trick SD3 uses (compute reference
//         locally with matching IEEE-754 ops).
//   NOT : integrated into ag_tape or ag_derive. Once SD5 lands,
//         SD6 (future cycle) can wire the AST extractor into
//         ag_derive's rule registry — but that is explicitly a
//         separate cycle per the scoping note §4.
//
// Hexa-native CPU only ($0). Strict-lint: @raw117_exempt (mirrors
// nn_lib / ag_tape / ag_derive convention).
//
// Atlas anchor (g6 — the reverse-mode rules ARE the citations):
//   - Pearlmutter & Siskind, "Reverse-Mode AD in a Functional
//     Framework: Lambda the Ultimate Backpropagator" (2008), ACM
//     TOPLAS 30(2). Establishes that reverse-mode AD is a
//     source-to-source program transform over the lambda calculus —
//     each language construct (let, if, application) has a
//     compositional vjp transformation rule. The SD5 walker
//     reproduces the If-construct rule (case 8 of the paper's
//     transformation tables).
//   - Griewank & Walther, "Evaluating Derivatives: Principles and
//     Techniques of Algorithmic Differentiation" (2008, SIAM, 2nd
//     ed). Chapter 3 establishes the reverse-mode chain rule
//     algorithmically; Chapter 4 covers branch-conditioned
//     primitives (the relu case = chapter 4.4's "kinks").
//   - For relu specifically: the closed-form vjp for the
//     conditional `y = if cond(x) then f(x) else g(x)` is
//     `dx = if cond(x) then df/dx · dy else dg/dx · dy`. For relu,
//     f(x) = x ⇒ df/dx = 1, g(x) = 0 ⇒ dg/dx = 0, so
//     `dx = if x > 0 then dy else 0`. This is the standard
//     subgradient choice at the kink x = 0 (df/dx | x=0 = 0); see
//     Griewank–Walther §4.4.2.
//   - Citation: hexa-lang.atlas (built-in) — the If-construct
//     reverse-mode rule. The walker's job is to recognize the
//     forward shape and apply the rule; the rule itself is the
//     atlas entry.
// ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

use "stdlib/flame/tensor_lib"
use "stdlib/flame/flame_math"  // dt_exp — primitive Taylor-based exp used by the sigmoid fwd

// ─── AST node kinds (encoded as small integers, farr-backed) ───────────
// The minimum kinds SD5 needs for the relu pattern. Kinds are encoded as
// integer codes (1..N) and stored in cell 0 of each node's metadata farr.
//
// Why farr-backed (not `pub struct`): flame stdlib convention. ag_tape /
// ag_derive / ag_spec all encode their structured records as flat farrs
// for trace-byte-eq fidelity with hand-derived references. SD5 follows
// the same idiom so future cycles can splice the AST into ag_spec or
// ag_tape recorders without struct↔farr conversion cost.
//
// Node kind code legend:
//   1 = Param      — function parameter, identified by index (0 = x, 1 = dy, …)
//                    metadata farr: [kind=1, param_index, 0, 0]
//                    children: none
//   2 = Const      — float literal (e.g. 0.0)
//                    metadata farr: [kind=2, 0, 0, 0]
//                    value lives in node's `value_farr[0]` (separate farr)
//                    children: none
//   3 = BinOp_GT   — binary >, returns bool-as-float (1.0 / 0.0)
//                    metadata farr: [kind=3, 0, 0, 0]
//                    children: [lhs_node, rhs_node]
//   4 = IfElse     — if cond then then_branch else else_branch
//                    metadata farr: [kind=4, 0, 0, 0]
//                    children: [cond_node, then_node, else_node]
//   5 = Var_Upstream  — synthetic node introduced by the reverse walk,
//                       references the upstream gradient (`dy`) by name.
//                       Used in the EMITTED bwd AST only (never appears
//                       in the fwd AST).
//                       metadata farr: [kind=5, 0, 0, 0]
//                       children: none
//   6 = BinOp_MUL  — synthetic node introduced by the reverse walk; the
//                    reverse-mode rule for an If branch is
//                    "select-mask · upstream", and a MUL node is one way
//                    to express it. NOT needed for the relu vjp (the rule
//                    collapses to IfElse(cond, dy, 0)); reserved for
//                    future SDs.
//                    metadata farr: [kind=6, 0, 0, 0]
//                    children: [lhs, rhs]
// SD6 (this cycle) adds:
//   7  = BinOp_ADD   — binary +
//                      metadata farr: [kind=7, 0, 0, 0]
//                      children: [lhs, rhs]
//   8  = BinOp_SUB   — binary −
//                      metadata farr: [kind=8, 0, 0, 0]
//                      children: [lhs, rhs]
//   9  = BinOp_DIV   — binary /
//                      metadata farr: [kind=9, 0, 0, 0]
//                      children: [lhs, rhs]
//   10 = BinOp_NEG   — unary −  (child[0] = operand)
//                      metadata farr: [kind=10, 0, 0, 0]
//                      children: [operand, -1, -1, -1]
//   11 = Call_DTEXP  — primitive call dt_exp(operand)
//                      metadata farr: [kind=11, 0, 0, 0]
//                      children: [operand, -1, -1, -1]
//   12 = Var_FwdResult — references a cached forward intermediate by
//                        slot-id. Used by the reverse-mode walker so
//                        the bwd AST can reuse forward results
//                        ("save forward, reuse in backward" — the
//                        sigmoid vjp pattern: `s = 1/(1+exp(-x))`
//                        appears in the bwd as `dx = dy * s * (1-s)`).
//                        metadata farr: [kind=12, fwd_node_id, 0, 0]
//                        children: none
//
// Reserved (future SDs): 13 = MatMul, 14 = Sum, …

pub fn ag_extract_k_param()         -> int { return 1 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_const()         -> int { return 2 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_binop_gt()      -> int { return 3 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_ifelse()        -> int { return 4 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_var_upstream()  -> int { return 5 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_binop_mul()     -> int { return 6 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_binop_add()     -> int { return 7 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_binop_sub()     -> int { return 8 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_binop_div()     -> int { return 9 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_binop_neg()     -> int { return 10 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_call_dtexp()    -> int { return 11 }
pub fn ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult() -> int { return 12 }

// ─── AST arena (single-pool design) ────────────────────────────────────
// Each AST node is identified by a small integer id (slot index in the
// arena). The arena stores three parallel farrs:
//   - meta_farr   : 4 cells per slot — [kind, ix, 0, 0]
//   - value_farr  : 1 cell per slot — float literal value (kind=2 only)
//   - child_farr  : 4 cells per slot — up to 4 child slot-ids (-1 = none)
// Capacity is fixed (32 slots is enough for relu's 5-node fwd + 5-node
// bwd; future SDs can bump it). Allocation is bump-pointer.
//
// Why parallel farrs (not one fat record): farr_set/get only
// scalars; struct-of-arrays mirrors the ag_tape idiom (kind farr, ids
// farr, dims farr).

// Capacity bumped from 32 (SD5) to 64 to fit the sigmoid fwd AST
// (5 nodes: const_neg1, x, u=−x, e=exp(u), const_1, d=1+e, s=1/d → 7
// nodes) PLUS the per-intermediate Var_FwdResult cache nodes (+4)
// PLUS the bwd AST emitted by the reverse walker (~10–14 nodes).
// 64 leaves comfortable headroom for SD7+ extensions.
fn _ag_extract_capacity() -> int { return 64 }

// Arena holds 3 farr_ids + a bump pointer in a 4-cell handle farr:
//   [meta_id, value_id, child_id, next_slot]
pub fn ag_extract_arena_new() -> int {
    let arena_h = t_zeros(4)
    let meta  = t_zeros(_ag_extract_capacity() * 4)
    let value = t_zeros(_ag_extract_capacity())
    let child = t_zeros(_ag_extract_capacity() * 4)
    // initialize all child slots to -1 (no-child sentinel)
    let mut i = 0
    while i < _ag_extract_capacity() * 4 {
        t_set(child, i, 0.0 - 1.0)
        i = i + 1
    }
    t_set(arena_h, 0, to_float(meta))
    t_set(arena_h, 1, to_float(value))
    t_set(arena_h, 2, to_float(child))
    t_set(arena_h, 3, 0.0)
    return arena_h
}

fn _arena_meta(arena_h: int)  -> int { return to_int(t_get(arena_h, 0)) }
fn _arena_value(arena_h: int) -> int { return to_int(t_get(arena_h, 1)) }
fn _arena_child(arena_h: int) -> int { return to_int(t_get(arena_h, 2)) }
fn _arena_bump(arena_h: int)  -> int { return to_int(t_get(arena_h, 3)) }
fn _arena_set_bump(arena_h: int, n: int) { t_set(arena_h, 3, to_float(n)) }

// Allocate a new slot, return its id (0..capacity).
fn _arena_alloc(arena_h: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_bump(arena_h)
    _arena_set_bump(arena_h, s + 1)
    return s
}

// Node-constructor helpers — emit a new slot, write its meta+children.
pub fn ag_extract_mk_param(arena: int, ix: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_param()))
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 1, to_float(ix))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_const(arena: int, v: float) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_const()))
    let vfarr = _arena_value(arena)
    t_set(vfarr, s, v)
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_binop_gt(arena: int, lhs: int, rhs: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_binop_gt()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(lhs))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 1, to_float(rhs))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_ifelse(arena: int, cond: int, t_branch: int, e_branch: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_ifelse()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(cond))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 1, to_float(t_branch))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 2, to_float(e_branch))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_var_upstream(arena: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_var_upstream()))
    return s
}

// SD6: binary-op MUL constructor (already had the kind code; needed
// for the reverse walker's emit path — sigmoid bwd uses MUL heavily).
pub fn ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena: int, lhs: int, rhs: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_binop_mul()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(lhs))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 1, to_float(rhs))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena: int, lhs: int, rhs: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_binop_add()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(lhs))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 1, to_float(rhs))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_binop_sub(arena: int, lhs: int, rhs: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_binop_sub()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(lhs))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 1, to_float(rhs))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_binop_div(arena: int, lhs: int, rhs: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_binop_div()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(lhs))
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 1, to_float(rhs))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_binop_neg(arena: int, operand: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_binop_neg()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(operand))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_mk_call_dtexp(arena: int, operand: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_call_dtexp()))
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    t_set(c, s * 4 + 0, to_float(operand))
    return s
}

// Var_FwdResult — refers to a cached forward intermediate by its
// fwd-arena slot id. The reverse-mode walker constructs these so
// the bwd AST can reuse forward results (the "save forward, reuse
// in backward" pattern). For sigmoid: `s = 1/(1+exp(-x))` is cached;
// the bwd reads it as `Var_FwdResult(s_node_id)`.
pub fn ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena: int, fwd_node_id: int) -> int {
    let s = _arena_alloc(arena)
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 0, to_float(ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult()))
    t_set(m, s * 4 + 1, to_float(fwd_node_id))
    return s
}

pub fn ag_extract_fwdresult_id(arena: int, node: int) -> int {
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    return to_int(t_get(m, node * 4 + 1))
}

// Node-introspection helpers.
pub fn ag_extract_kind(arena: int, node: int) -> int {
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    return to_int(t_get(m, node * 4 + 0))
}

pub fn ag_extract_param_ix(arena: int, node: int) -> int {
    let m = _arena_meta(arena)
    return to_int(t_get(m, node * 4 + 1))
}

pub fn ag_extract_const_value(arena: int, node: int) -> float {
    let v = _arena_value(arena)
    return t_get(v, node)
}

pub fn ag_extract_child(arena: int, node: int, i: int) -> int {
    let c = _arena_child(arena)
    return to_int(t_get(c, node * 4 + i))
}

// ─── forward AST builder: relu(x) = if x > 0 then x else 0 ─────────────
// Hand-builds the fwd AST. In SD5 this stands in for what a real parser
// would produce when fed `pub fn relu(x: float) -> float { if x > 0.0
// { x } else { 0.0 } }`. SD5's purpose is the WALKER, not the parser —
// the AST shape here is identical to what the real parser emits for
// the relu source (verifiable by comparing against compiler/parse/
// ast.hexa::Expr with kind ExprKind::If wrapping a BinOp wrapping
// Ident "x" + LiteralFloat 0.0). Future SDs reuse the same walker
// against the parser-built AST.
//
// Returned root node id is the IfElse expression.
pub fn ag_extract_build_relu_fwd(arena: int) -> int {
    // x (param index 0)
    let x_node    = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)
    // 0.0 (literal)
    let zero_node = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    // x > 0.0
    let cond_node = ag_extract_mk_binop_gt(arena, x_node, zero_node)
    // then-branch = x (we reuse the same param-node id; AST is a DAG
    // in this minimal encoding, but the walker treats it as a tree
    // for the purposes of vjp emission — Param has no children, so
    // sharing is safe)
    // else-branch = 0.0 (we make a fresh const node so the AST is
    // structurally a tree)
    let else_node = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    let root      = ag_extract_mk_ifelse(arena, cond_node, x_node, else_node)
    return root
}

// ─── SD6 forward AST builder: sigmoid(x) = 1.0/(1.0+dt_exp(-x)) ────────
// Hand-builds the sigmoid fwd AST. Same hand-build convention as SD5 —
// stands in for what the parser would produce for
//   `pub fn sigmoid(x: float) -> float { return 1.0 / (1.0 + dt_exp(0.0 - x)) }`
// (we use `0.0 − x` rather than the unary `-x` so the AST shape mirrors
// what an honest parser would emit; the BinOp_NEG kind is reserved for
// any future unary-prefix syntax).
//
// To support the "save forward result, reuse in backward" pattern, the
// builder writes the root slot-id into the caller-supplied 4-cell
// `cache_out` farr at index 0; the per-intermediate caches go at:
//   cache_out[0] = s_node (root, the sigmoid output)
//   cache_out[1] = d_node (1 + e)
//   cache_out[2] = e_node (dt_exp(u))
//   cache_out[3] = u_node (0 − x, the negated input)
// The reverse-mode walker reads these to construct Var_FwdResult nodes
// for each cached intermediate. (Future SDs replace this convention
// with a parser-emitted let-binding chain + ag_tape registry — SD7.)
//
// Returned: the s_node slot-id (sigmoid output).
pub fn ag_extract_build_sigmoid_fwd(arena: int, cache_out: int) -> int {
    // x (param index 0)
    let x_node      = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)
    // 0.0 (literal)
    let zero_node_a = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    // u = 0.0 − x  (the input negation)
    let u_node      = ag_extract_mk_binop_sub(arena, zero_node_a, x_node)
    // e = dt_exp(u)
    let e_node      = ag_extract_mk_call_dtexp(arena, u_node)
    // 1.0 (literal — used in two places, two separate const nodes
    // so the AST stays structurally a tree)
    let one_node_a  = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 1.0)
    // d = 1.0 + e
    let d_node      = ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, one_node_a, e_node)
    // 1.0 (literal, numerator)
    let one_node_b  = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 1.0)
    // s = 1.0 / d
    let s_node      = ag_extract_mk_binop_div(arena, one_node_b, d_node)
    // Publish the cache slots so the reverse walker can wire
    // Var_FwdResult nodes to each intermediate.
    t_set(cache_out, 0, to_float(s_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 1, to_float(d_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 2, to_float(e_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 3, to_float(u_node))
    return s_node
}

// ─── reverse-mode walker ───────────────────────────────────────────────
// `ag_extract_reverse_walk(fwd_arena, fwd_root, target_param_ix)` —
// performs reverse-mode AD on the fwd AST and emits a bwd AST in the
// SAME arena (the bwd nodes are appended after the fwd nodes; the
// returned id points at the bwd root).
//
// The rule SD5 implements (the only one needed for relu):
//
//   reverse_walk(IfElse(cond, then_branch, else_branch), target_param) =
//     IfElse(
//       cond,
//       reverse_walk(then_branch, target_param),      # then-side contrib
//       reverse_walk(else_branch, target_param)       # else-side contrib
//     )
//
//   reverse_walk(Param(i), target_param) =
//     if i == target_param then Var_Upstream() else Const(0.0)
//
//   reverse_walk(Const(_), target_param) =
//     Const(0.0)
//
//   reverse_walk(BinOp_GT(_, _), target_param) =
//     UNUSED (a comparison's gradient is 0 a.e.; in the IfElse rule
//     above we DON'T re-walk the condition — its job is to be tested,
//     not differentiated. This matches Griewank–Walther §4.4.2's
//     treatment of "indicator functions": the reverse-mode dataflow
//     does not flow through the condition, only through the selected
//     branch.)
//
// For relu, applying these rules to the fwd AST
//   IfElse(GT(x, 0), x, 0)
// produces
//   IfElse(GT(x, 0), Var_Upstream, Const(0.0))
// which is exactly `dx = if x > 0 then dy else 0` — the standard
// relu vjp.
pub fn ag_extract_reverse_walk(arena: int, fwd_node: int, target_param_ix: int) -> int {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, fwd_node)

    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, fwd_node)
        if ix == target_param_ix {
            return ag_extract_mk_var_upstream(arena)
        }
        return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_ifelse() {
        let cond     = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let t_branch = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 1)
        let e_branch = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 2)
        let bwd_t = ag_extract_reverse_walk(arena, t_branch, target_param_ix)
        let bwd_e = ag_extract_reverse_walk(arena, e_branch, target_param_ix)
        // re-use the original cond node (the condition is shared between
        // fwd and bwd ASTs — it's evaluated against the same `x` at
        // runtime, no reverse-mode transformation needed)
        return ag_extract_mk_ifelse(arena, cond, bwd_t, bwd_e)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_gt() {
        // The comparison itself is not differentiated. If we encounter
        // a GT NODE in a position that the IfElse rule does not consume,
        // SD5 treats it as a constant 0.0 contribution (subgradient = 0
        // a.e. — Griewank–Walther §4.4.1). For the relu fwd this branch
        // is unreachable (GT only appears as an IfElse condition); we
        // include it for completeness so the walker doesn't fault on
        // future patterns.
        return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    }

    // Unsupported kind for SD5. In a richer cycle we'd recurse on
    // children; SD5 keeps the surface small.
    return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
}

// ─── SD6: reverse-mode walker v2 with explicit upstream-gradient ───────
// `ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, fwd_node, upstream_grad_node,
//  target_param_ix)` — the chain-rule-threaded reverse walker. Unlike
// the SD5 walker (which folds the upstream into the recursion implicitly
// via Var_Upstream leaves), v2 takes an EXPLICIT upstream-grad AST node
// and propagates the chain rule top-down through each fwd-node's
// per-op rule. This is the Wengert-tape shape (Griewank–Walther §3.2
// elementary primitives table; Pearlmutter & Siskind §3 lambda-the-
// ultimate compositional vjp transformer).
//
// Per-op rules (each is an atlas-bound theorem; @cite via header):
//   c = a + b   → da_contrib = dc           , db_contrib = dc
//   c = a − b   → da_contrib = dc           , db_contrib = NEG(dc)
//   c = a × b   → da_contrib = dc × b_cached, db_contrib = dc × a_cached
//   c = a / b   → da_contrib = dc / b       ,
//                 db_contrib = NEG(dc × c_cached / b)
//                 (the "/b² → c/b" reuse: c = a/b ⇒ a/(b²) = c/b)
//   c = NEG(a)  → da_contrib = NEG(dc)
//   c = dt_exp(a) → da_contrib = dc × c_cached
//                   (d/da exp(a) = exp(a); reuse cached forward result)
//
// Where "cached" means: a Var_FwdResult node pointing at the
// corresponding fwd-AST slot. The interpret step (below) maintains
// a fwd-value cache keyed by fwd-slot-id so each cached intermediate
// is computed at most once.
//
// For sigmoid `s = 1/(1+exp(0−x))` walked from upstream = Var_Upstream
// (= dy), v2 produces a bwd AST that — when interpreted — computes
//   dx = NEG(dy × s_cached × e_cached / d_cached)
// (with extra NEG cancellation; the rule chain yields a literal tree
// the interpret step evaluates). Mathematically this equals
//   dx = dy × s × (1 − s)
// (algebraic identity: 1 − s = e/d, so s × e/d = s × (1−s)). Whether
// IEEE-754 byte-eq holds against the `dy × s × (1.0 − s)` hand-written
// reference is an empirical question — different float trajectories
// can differ in the last bit. SD6's byte-eq oracle measures this and
// reports the verdict honestly.
//
// Recursion design: each call returns ONE bwd-AST node representing
// the gradient contribution flowing into the fwd-node's output. For
// fwd-nodes with multiple children (binops), the rules above describe
// how to combine the parent's `dc` with each child's local derivative
// to form THAT child's `dc` — then the walker recurses on the child
// with that derived `dc`. The Param/Const leaves stop the recursion:
// Param-match returns the accumulated upstream; non-match returns 0.
//
// Multi-use of the same fwd-node (gradient accumulation across multiple
// paths) is NOT supported in v2 — SD6 limits itself to fwd graphs
// where each intermediate has exactly one use (sigmoid satisfies this).
// True accumulation requires a Wengert registry, which is the SD7
// scope (per scoping note §4).
pub fn ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena: int, fwd_node: int,
                                   upstream_grad: int,
                                   target_param_ix: int) -> int {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, fwd_node)

    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, fwd_node)
        if ix == target_param_ix {
            return upstream_grad
        }
        return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        // c = a + b ⇒ da_contrib = dc, db_contrib = dc
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 1)
        let ga = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, a, upstream_grad, target_param_ix)
        let gb = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, b, upstream_grad, target_param_ix)
        // Combine via ADD. (For sigmoid's structure only one of {ga, gb}
        // is a non-zero contribution along the path to x; the other
        // reduces to Const(0.0). We keep the ADD for generality.)
        return ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, ga, gb)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        // c = a − b ⇒ da_contrib = dc, db_contrib = NEG(dc)
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 1)
        let ga = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, a, upstream_grad, target_param_ix)
        let neg_up = ag_extract_mk_binop_neg(arena, upstream_grad)
        let gb = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, b, neg_up, target_param_ix)
        return ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, ga, gb)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        // c = a × b ⇒ da_contrib = dc × b, db_contrib = dc × a
        // (we use the fwd-cached values via Var_FwdResult so the bwd
        //  reuses forward intermediates rather than re-traversing the
        //  fwd sub-AST in the interpret step)
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 1)
        let b_cached = ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena, b)
        let a_cached = ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena, a)
        let dc_b = ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena, upstream_grad, b_cached)
        let dc_a = ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena, upstream_grad, a_cached)
        let ga = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, a, dc_b, target_param_ix)
        let gb = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, b, dc_a, target_param_ix)
        return ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, ga, gb)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        // c = a / b ⇒
        //   da_contrib = dc / b
        //   db_contrib = NEG(dc × c / b)
        //   (uses cached `c` = fwd-result of this very node; the
        //    standard "save forward, reuse in backward" pattern.)
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 1)
        let b_cached = ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena, b)
        let c_cached = ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena, fwd_node)
        // da_contrib = upstream / b
        let da_local = ag_extract_mk_binop_div(arena, upstream_grad, b_cached)
        // db_contrib = NEG(upstream × c / b)
        let b_cached_2 = ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena, b)
        let up_c       = ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena, upstream_grad, c_cached)
        let up_c_over_b = ag_extract_mk_binop_div(arena, up_c, b_cached_2)
        let db_local   = ag_extract_mk_binop_neg(arena, up_c_over_b)
        let ga = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, a, da_local, target_param_ix)
        let gb = ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, b, db_local, target_param_ix)
        return ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, ga, gb)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        // c = NEG(a) ⇒ da_contrib = NEG(dc)
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let neg_up = ag_extract_mk_binop_neg(arena, upstream_grad)
        return ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, a, neg_up, target_param_ix)
    }

    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        // c = dt_exp(a) ⇒ da_contrib = dc × c (reuse cached fwd result)
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, fwd_node, 0)
        let c_cached = ag_extract_mk_var_fwdresult(arena, fwd_node)
        let dc_c = ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena, upstream_grad, c_cached)
        return ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2(arena, a, dc_c, target_param_ix)
    }

    // Unsupported kind for SD6. v2 keeps SD5's surface (IfElse, GT)
    // out-of-scope — those are SD5-walker territory; future SDs will
    // unify the two walkers.
    return ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
}

// ─── emit step: bwd AST → hexa-lang source string ──────────────────────
// `ag_extract_emit(arena, bwd_root, fn_name)` — pretty-prints the bwd
// AST as a hexa-lang function definition. The output is HUMAN-READABLE
// hexa source that COULD be compiled standalone (the test prints it for
// inspection — see flame_ag_extract_test.hexa). The interpret path
// (below) avoids the second-compile dependency for the byte-eq oracle.
//
// Function signature emitted (for relu):
//   pub fn <fn_name>(x: float, dy: float) -> float {
//       return <body>
//   }
// where <body> is the recursive emission of the bwd-root expression.
pub fn ag_extract_emit_expr(arena: int, node: int) -> string {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        // SD9 extends the 1-param "x" convention to a 2-param "(x, y)"
        // convention for the bilinear vjp test. Higher indices fall back
        // to the SD5 `p<ix>` naming. A future SD with parser integration
        // (SD8) will swap this for the parsed Param's actual identifier.
        if ix == 0 { return "x" }
        if ix == 1 { return "y" }
        return "p" + to_string(ix)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        let v = ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
        return float_to_string(v)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_gt() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + " > " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_ifelse() {
        let c = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let t_br = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let e_br = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 2)
        return "(if " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, c)
             + " { " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, t_br)
             + " } else { " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, e_br) + " })"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_upstream() {
        return "dy"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + " * " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    // SD6 emit cases — mirror the new node kinds.
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + " + " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + " - " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + " / " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return "(0.0 - " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return "dt_exp(" + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, l) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult() {
        let fid = ag_extract_fwdresult_id(arena, node)
        // The emit step prints fwd-result references symbolically; the
        // emitted source would compile against a precomputed fwd-cache.
        // Convention: name the cached forward value `_fwd<id>`.
        return "_fwd" + to_string(fid)
    }
    return "/* unsupported kind " + to_string(k) + " */"
}

// Helper: hexa stage0 has no built-in float→string with deterministic
// formatting (the println surface uses libc printf). For the SD5 emit
// step we only need to format 0.0, which is byte-stable. A real cycle
// would need a richer float-format helper; SD5 marks it as a known
// stop-condition.
fn float_to_string(v: float) -> string {
    if v == 0.0 { return "0.0" }
    if v == 1.0 { return "1.0" }
    // Conservative fallback — to_string on float is provided by the
    // tensor_lib surface (println uses it).
    return to_string(v)
}

pub fn ag_extract_emit_fn(arena: int, bwd_root: int, fn_name: string) -> string {
    return "pub fn " + fn_name + "(x: float, dy: float) -> float {\n"
         + "    return " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, bwd_root) + "\n"
         + "}\n"
}

// SD9: emit a per-Param backward function for a 2-input fwd `f(x, y)`.
// The signature carries BOTH inputs so a future re-compile pass can
// call `f_x_bwd_auto(x_i, y_i, dy_i)` and `f_y_bwd_auto(x_i, y_i, dy_i)`
// once per i in a tight loop. SD9 only renders this for inspection; the
// in-process byte-eq oracle goes through interpret_v2_multi.
pub fn ag_extract_emit_fn_xy(arena: int, bwd_root: int, fn_name: string) -> string {
    return "pub fn " + fn_name + "(x: float, y: float, dy: float) -> float {\n"
         + "    return " + ag_extract_emit_expr(arena, bwd_root) + "\n"
         + "}\n"
}

// SD11: emit a STANDALONE-COMPILABLE program — the bwd fn + an `fn main()`
// argv wrapper that lets the compiled binary be invoked as
//   ./bin <x_repr> <dy_repr>
// and emit one line on stdout: `to_string(dx)` (the runtime uses %.17g
// which round-trips losslessly via strtod, so the SD11 harness's
// `.to_float()` on this line recovers the IEEE-754 bit-pattern verbatim).
//
// Scope (SD11 honest scope, task brief §5): this helper is the SIMPLEST
// emit shape — single-Param, signature `(x: float, dy: float) -> float`.
// It matches SD5's relu walker output (a pure conditional, no fwd-cache,
// no Var_Upstream complications). Multi-input + arithmetic compile is
// SD12+ work; that requires emitting fwd-cache materialisation into the
// argv driver, which itself needs Var_FwdResult → recomputation.
//
// Atlas cite: @cite Griewank-Walther §3.2 elementary-vjp emit (the
// emitted source is the literal output of the reverse walker's emit;
// SD11 closes the AD loop end-to-end by recompiling that source).
//
// Round-trip invariant for byte-eq (binary64 IEEE-754):
//   compiled_binary(json_stringify(x), json_stringify(dy)).parse_first_line_as_float()
//     ≡  in_process_interpret(arena, bwd_root, x, dy)
// because (a) the emit prints `json_stringify(dx)` whose path goes
// through runtime_core.c::_shortest_double (loops 1..17 digit `%g` and
// strtod-checks each — see runtime.c:7909 comment block "shortest %g-form
// decimal that strtod-round-trips to the same double"); (b) the harness
// constructs argv args from `json_stringify(xi)` / `json_stringify(dyi)`
// using the same shortest-roundtrip codec; (c) `.to_float()` is
// strtod-backed (parses the shortest-roundtrip text back to the SAME
// double bit-for-bit); (d) the emitted source produces the SAME IEEE-754
// trajectory as the interpret walker — both go through the identical
// `>`-then-select dataflow on a single conditional.
//
// IMPORTANT: do NOT replace `json_stringify` with `to_string`. The
// hexa-native `to_string` for float (runtime_core.c:5078) uses `%g`
// (default 6 significant digits) which truncates to ~7 decimal places
// — round-trip loses 1e-7-scale precision and breaks byte-eq.
// json_stringify uses `_shortest_double` (round-trip safe).
pub fn ag_extract_emit_program_x_dy(arena: int, bwd_root: int, fn_name: string) -> string {
    let bwd_src = ag_extract_emit_fn(arena, bwd_root, fn_name)
    let mut main_src = ""
    main_src = main_src + "\n"
    main_src = main_src + "fn main() {\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let argv = args()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // argv layout when invoked directly: [bin, x_repr, dy_repr]\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    if len(argv) < 3 {\n"
    main_src = main_src + "        println(\"usage: <bin> <x> <dy>\")\n"
    main_src = main_src + "        exit(2)\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    }\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let x  = argv[1].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let dy = argv[2].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let dx = " + fn_name + "(x, dy)\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // json_stringify is round-trip safe (shortest %g-form\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // strtod-checked; runtime_core.c::_shortest_double).\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // Plain to_string(dx) uses %g (6 digits) — would lose\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // byte-eq across the recompile boundary.\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    println(json_stringify(dx))\n"
    main_src = main_src + "}\n"
    return bwd_src + main_src
}

// ─── SD12: multi-input compile-and-run emit ────────────────────────────
// `ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, node)` — variant of `emit_expr` that
// resolves a `Var_FwdResult(fid)` REFERENCING A PARAM directly back to
// that Param's identifier ("x" for Param(0), "y" for Param(1)).
//
// Why this is sound for SD12's scope (bilinear MUL `f(x, y) = x * y`):
// the reverse walker's MUL rule (ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2 §MUL) builds
// `b_cached = mk_var_fwdresult(a)` and `a_cached = mk_var_fwdresult(b)`
// where `a` and `b` are the MUL's children. For the bilinear fwd those
// children are Param(0) and Param(1) DIRECTLY — so every Var_FwdResult
// emitted by the SD9 bwd points to a Param leaf. The fwd-cache value
// for a Param leaf is, by `ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi`, exactly the
// argv-supplied float (no arithmetic intervenes). Therefore replacing
// `_fwd<param_node_id>` with the argv-bound identifier yields IDENTICAL
// IEEE-754 trajectory — the compiled binary executes the same scalar
// expression the in-process `interpret_v2_multi` walker evaluates.
//
// Sub-AST graphs whose Var_FwdResult points to a NON-Param node (SD13+
// scope: sigmoid, sigmoid-div, multi-use intermediates — all use the
// `_fwd<id>` symbol that names a precomputed intermediate) fall back
// to the SD11 `_fwd<id>` lexeme, leaving them as a clearly visible
// compile-time-undefined-variable error rather than silently producing
// wrong gradients. SD13+ will materialise the fwd-cache pre-call inside
// `fn main()` to close those shapes.
//
// Atlas cite: @cite Griewank-Walther §3.2 "Reverse Mode" — the bwd AST
// node `a_cached = b` follows directly from the MUL VJP rule
// `da = dc · b`; SD12 emits that `b` by resolving the symbolic
// fwd-cache reference back to its Param identifier.
pub fn ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena: int, node: int) -> string {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult() {
        let fid = ag_extract_fwdresult_id(arena, node)
        let target_k = ag_extract_kind(arena, fid)
        if target_k == ag_extract_k_param() {
            // The fwd-cache value of a Param leaf equals the Param's
            // argv-supplied scalar verbatim (eval_fwd_multi's Param
            // branch writes `param_vals[ix]` into fwd_cache[node] then
            // returns it). Emitting the identifier directly preserves
            // byte-eq with interpret_v2_multi.
            let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, fid)
            if ix == 0 { return "x" }
            if ix == 1 { return "y" }
            return "p" + to_string(ix)
        }
        // SD13+ scope: fwd-cache references to non-Param intermediates
        // need an emitted pre-call materialisation. SD12 punts via the
        // SD11 `_fwd<id>` lexeme (kept identical so any accidental SD13
        // overlap shows up as an obvious compile error, not silent
        // miscompile).
        return "_fwd" + to_string(fid)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        if ix == 0 { return "x" }
        if ix == 1 { return "y" }
        return "p" + to_string(ix)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        let v = ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
        return float_to_string(v)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_upstream() {
        return "dy"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + " + " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + " - " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + " * " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + " / " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return "(0.0 - " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_gt() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return "(" + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + " > " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, r) + ")"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_ifelse() {
        let c = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let t_br = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let e_br = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 2)
        return "(if " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, c)
             + " { " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, t_br)
             + " } else { " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, e_br) + " })"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return "dt_exp(" + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, l) + ")"
    }
    return "/* unsupported kind " + to_string(k) + " */"
}

// SD12: emit a STANDALONE-COMPILABLE program for a per-Param bwd of a
// 2-input fwd `f(x, y)`. Mirrors `ag_extract_emit_program_x_dy` (SD11)
// but reads THREE floats from argv (x · y · dy), calls a 3-arg bwd fn,
// and emits one shortest-roundtrip line via `json_stringify`. Used by
// the SD12 harness to compile both `f_x_bwd_auto` and `f_y_bwd_auto`
// derived from the bilinear MUL fwd, then exec each binary 32× and
// three-way byte-eq the output against the in-process interpret walker
// and the hand reference.
//
// Honest scope (SD12, g3): for `f(x, y) = x * y`, the SD9 reverse_walk_v2
// MUL rule produces a bwd AST containing ONLY Var_FwdResult nodes that
// target Params — `emit_expr_xy` resolves these to their identifiers.
// Other fwds (sigmoid, sigmoid-div, multi-use) require fwd-cache
// materialisation INSIDE the emitted main(); that is SD13+ work.
//
// Atlas cite: @cite Griewank-Walther §3.2 elementary-vjp emit (multi-input
// extension is the natural generalisation: the reverse walker stays the
// same, the emit step gains a 3-arg argv reader; the bwd AST already
// reads `x`, `y`, `dy` as named leaves; SD11's round-trip lemma carries
// over verbatim).
//
// Round-trip invariant for byte-eq (binary64 IEEE-754):
//   compiled_binary(json_stringify(x), json_stringify(y), json_stringify(dy))
//     .parse_first_line_as_float()
//   ≡  ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, bwd_root, [x, y], dy, fwd_cache)
//   ≡  hand_reference(x, y, dy)
// where `hand_reference(x, y, dy) = dy * y + 0.0` for df/dx and
// `0.0 + dy * x` for df/dy (the Option-A reorder-match the SD9 manual
// uses; both columns flow through identical IEEE-754 ops).
pub fn ag_extract_emit_program_xy_dy(arena: int, bwd_root: int, fn_name: string) -> string {
    let mut bwd_src = "pub fn " + fn_name + "(x: float, y: float, dy: float) -> float {\n"
    bwd_src = bwd_src + "    return " + ag_extract_emit_expr_xy(arena, bwd_root) + "\n"
    bwd_src = bwd_src + "}\n"
    let mut main_src = ""
    main_src = main_src + "\n"
    main_src = main_src + "fn main() {\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let argv = args()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // argv layout when invoked directly: [bin, x_repr, y_repr, dy_repr]\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    if len(argv) < 4 {\n"
    main_src = main_src + "        println(\"usage: <bin> <x> <y> <dy>\")\n"
    main_src = main_src + "        exit(2)\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    }\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let x  = argv[1].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let y  = argv[2].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let dy = argv[3].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let d_param = " + fn_name + "(x, y, dy)\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // json_stringify is round-trip safe (shortest %g-form\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // strtod-checked; runtime_core.c::_shortest_double).\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // Plain to_string for float uses %g (6 digits) — would\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // lose byte-eq across the recompile boundary.\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    println(json_stringify(d_param))\n"
    main_src = main_src + "}\n"
    return bwd_src + main_src
}

// ─── SD13: fwd-cache materialisation inside emitted main() ─────────────
// `ag_extract_emit_fwd_let(arena, node) -> string` — render a single
// `let _fwd<id>: float = <expr>` binding for fwd-AST node `id`, where
// `<expr>` reads its direct children as `_fwd<child_id>` references
// (Params resolve to the argv-bound identifier `x`; Consts to their
// scalar literal). The recursion is structural — no traversal of
// descendants here; the caller emits bindings in slot-id order so
// each child binding is already in scope when its parent reads it.
//
// IEEE-754 byte-eq: the emitted expression sequence executes the
// SAME ops in the SAME order as `ag_extract_eval_fwd` in-process —
// (Param→x) leaves write the argv value verbatim, BinOp_ADD emits
// `(_fwda + _fwdb)` matching `va + vb`, etc. Same scalar ops, same
// operand order ⇒ identical IEEE-754 trajectory ⇒ same fwd_cache
// content as the interpret path ⇒ same `_fwd<id>` symbols feed the
// walker-emitted bwd body byte-identically.
//
// SD13 honest scope: this helper expects a fwd AST that uses ONLY
// the kinds the walker's interpret/eval surface handles —
// Param · Const · BinOp_ADD/SUB/MUL/DIV/NEG · Call_DTEXP. Unknown
// kinds emit `/* unsupported kind N */` as a clearly-visible compile
// error sentinel (matches the SD11/SD12 `emit_expr*` fallback idiom).
//
// Atlas cite: @cite Griewank-Walther §3.2 "save forward, reuse in
// backward" — the let-binding chain materialises the Wengert tape
// in source form; SD13 is the first SD to land that materialisation
// inside compiled hexa code.
pub fn ag_extract_emit_fwd_let(arena: int, node: int) -> string {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    let id_str = to_string(node)
    let prefix = "    let _fwd" + id_str + ": float = "
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        // SD13 scope: emitted main reads ONE argv float (named `x`);
        // bind any Param leaf to `x` (matches `eval_fwd` Param branch
        // which writes x_val for ix==0). Multi-input fwd-cache
        // materialisation (SD13 bonus path) is `emit_fwd_let_xy`.
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        if ix == 0 { return prefix + "x\n" }
        return prefix + "0.0  /* SD13: Param(ix=" + to_string(ix) + ") in single-input scope */\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        let v = ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
        return prefix + float_to_string(v) + "\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_fwd" + to_string(a) + " + _fwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_fwd" + to_string(a) + " - _fwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_fwd" + to_string(a) + " * _fwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_fwd" + to_string(a) + " / _fwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return prefix + "(0.0 - _fwd" + to_string(a) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return prefix + "dt_exp(_fwd" + to_string(a) + ")\n"
    }
    // Unsupported kind: emit a syntactically-visible sentinel so the
    // hexa-build step rejects the source instead of silently producing
    // wrong gradients. Same idiom as `emit_expr` for unknown kinds.
    return prefix + "0.0  /* SD13: unsupported fwd kind " + to_string(k) + " */\n"
}

// `ag_extract_emit_program_x_dy_with_fwd_cache(arena, fwd_root, bwd_root,
//  fn_name) -> string` — SD13's primary deliverable. Emits a
// STANDALONE-COMPILABLE program that (a) defines the bwd fn whose body
// references `_fwd<id>` symbols for each non-Param fwd-cache slot, and
// (b) materialises every fwd-cache slot 0..fwd_root inside `fn main()`
// as `let _fwd<id>: float = <expr>` bindings BEFORE calling the bwd fn.
//
// Architecture: the bwd fn signature stays `(x: float, dy: float, _fwd0: float,
// _fwd1: float, ...) -> float` — one extra parameter per fwd slot id 0..fwd_root.
// `fn main()` materialises each `_fwd<id>` from the fwd AST, in slot-id
// order (the fwd AST is built bottom-up so slot-id order IS topological
// order — children have smaller ids than their parents). The bwd fn
// body's `_fwd<id>` lexemes (emitted by `ag_extract_emit_expr`) now
// resolve to the corresponding parameter, byte-eq with the in-process
// `interpret_v2` (which reads `fwd_cache[id]`).
//
// Round-trip invariant (binary64 IEEE-754):
//   compiled_binary(json_stringify(x), json_stringify(dy))
//     .first_line_as_float()
//     ≡  ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, bwd_root, x, dy, populated_fwd_cache)
//     ≡  hand_reference(x, dy)        // up to SD6's algebraic-identity
//                                     // 1-ULP zone if the walker emits
//                                     // e/d while the hand form uses 1-s
// because (a) `emit_fwd_let` mirrors `eval_fwd`'s scalar op sequence
// byte-identically; (b) the bwd body emitted by `emit_expr` reads
// `_fwd<id>` parameters that hold those byte-identical fwd values; and
// (c) `json_stringify` + `.to_float()` round-trip is shortest-double
// strtod-safe (SD11 lemma).
//
// Honest scope (SD13, g3):
//   - PROVES: walker-emit→compile→run round-trip works for ANY fwd AST
//     whose bwd references non-Param fwd-cache slots (sigmoid, sigmoid-div,
//     multi-use intermediates — all the SD6/SD7/SD10 shapes).
//   - INHERITS: SD6's 1-ULP zone for sigmoid — the walker emits
//     `dy × s × e/d` (algebraic identity to `dy × s × (1−s)` but
//     different IEEE-754 trajectory). SD13's compile path produces the
//     SAME 1-ULP delta vs the hand-derived `dy × s × (1−s)`. This is a
//     CONFIRMATION of SD6's finding at the compile boundary, NOT a
//     regression.
//   - DOES NOT change: SD11/SD12 surfaces (`emit_program_x_dy`,
//     `emit_program_xy_dy`) — those remain the simpler emit shapes
//     used when no fwd-cache materialisation is needed.
//
// Atlas cite: @cite Griewank-Walther §3.2 Algorithm 3.6 (reverse-mode
// emit with cached forward values) + Steele-White 1990 (shortest-roundtrip
// decimal lemma for binary64).
// `ag_extract_emit_bwd_let(arena, node, fwd_root) -> string` — render a
// single `let _bwd<id>: float = <expr>` binding for bwd-AST node `id`,
// where `<expr>` reads its direct children either as `_fwd<child_id>`
// (when the child is a fwd-arena Var_FwdResult — resolved to its fid),
// `_bwd<child_id>` (when the child is a bwd-arena node — id > fwd_root),
// or `dy` (when the child is Var_Upstream), or `x` (when the child is
// Param ix=0), or a literal (when the child is Const).
//
// FMA-fence rationale: the in-process interpret path evaluates each
// bwd binop via a function call (interpret_v2 recurses, each return
// is a separate IEEE-754 op). The emitted bwd body, if rendered as
// one giant chained expression, lets clang's `-ffp-contract=on`
// (the arm64 default) fuse `a*b + c` patterns into FMA instructions,
// producing a different last-bit trajectory than the interp path
// (measured 2-ULP delta in SD13 dev). Storing every intermediate in
// a `let` binding gives clang nothing to fuse across — each binop
// produces a named SSA value that survives optimisation, matching
// the interp path byte-identically.
//
// Atlas cite: @cite c0789e05 "`#pragma STDC FP_CONTRACT OFF` for CPU
// raw-double mirrors" — same architectural lesson: name every binop's
// result so the optimiser cannot reorder/fuse across them.
pub fn ag_extract_emit_bwd_let(arena: int, node: int, fwd_root: int) -> string {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    let id_str = to_string(node)
    let prefix = "    let _bwd" + id_str + ": float = "
    // Leaves: bind to constants / argv-bound / fwd-cache slots.
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        return prefix + float_to_string(ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)) + "\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_upstream() {
        return prefix + "dy\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        if ix == 0 { return prefix + "x\n" }
        return prefix + "0.0  /* SD13: Param(ix=" + to_string(ix) + ") in single-input scope */\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult() {
        let fid = ag_extract_fwdresult_id(arena, node)
        return prefix + "_fwd" + to_string(fid) + "\n"
    }
    // Inner nodes: read each child as _bwd<child_id> (every prior bwd
    // node is already bound in topological order — `node` > children
    // because the walker built children first).
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_bwd" + to_string(a) + " + _bwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_bwd" + to_string(a) + " - _bwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_bwd" + to_string(a) + " * _bwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return prefix + "(_bwd" + to_string(a) + " / _bwd" + to_string(b) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return prefix + "(0.0 - _bwd" + to_string(a) + ")\n"
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return prefix + "dt_exp(_bwd" + to_string(a) + ")\n"
    }
    return prefix + "0.0  /* SD13: unsupported bwd kind " + to_string(k) + " */\n"
}

pub fn ag_extract_emit_program_x_dy_with_fwd_cache(arena: int, fwd_root: int,
                                                    bwd_root: int,
                                                    fn_name: string) -> string {
    // ─── stdlib imports (dt_exp lives in stdlib/flame/flame_math) ──
    // The walker emits `dt_exp(_fwd<id>)` for the Call_DTEXP rule (used
    // by sigmoid: e = dt_exp(u)). The fwd-cache materialisation in
    // main() also calls `dt_exp` to populate the corresponding slot.
    // Without this `use` the emitted source references undefined
    // identifiers; clang barfs at the C-codegen stage.
    let mut bwd_src = "use \"stdlib/flame/flame_math\"\n"

    // SD13 emits the bwd computation INLINE in main() rather than as a
    // separate fn, to keep all binops at the same lexical scope as the
    // `_fwd<id>` materialisation lines and to give clang nothing to
    // FMA-fuse across (per `emit_bwd_let` rationale). The `fn_name`
    // argument is preserved in a comment for inspection; future
    // expansions can resurrect a per-vjp fn boundary by emitting the
    // bwd letseq inside a synthesised function body.
    bwd_src = bwd_src + "// SD13: " + fn_name
            + " — bwd materialised inline in main() (FMA-fence pattern).\n"

    // ─── fn main(): argv reader + fwd-cache materialisation + bwd-let seq ──
    let mut main_src = ""
    main_src = main_src + "\n"
    main_src = main_src + "fn main() {\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let argv = args()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // argv layout: [bin, x_repr, dy_repr]\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    if len(argv) < 3 {\n"
    main_src = main_src + "        println(\"usage: <bin> <x> <dy>\")\n"
    main_src = main_src + "        exit(2)\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    }\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let x  = argv[1].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    let dy = argv[2].to_float()\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // ── fwd-cache materialisation (SD13 §3.2 Wengert tape) ──\n"
    let mut sid = 0
    while sid <= fwd_root {
        main_src = main_src + ag_extract_emit_fwd_let(arena, sid)
        sid = sid + 1
    }
    // ── bwd materialisation as a letseq (FMA fence). Every bwd-AST
    // node id from fwd_root+1 .. bwd_root gets its own `let _bwd<id>:
    // float = ...` line. Topological order is guaranteed because the
    // walker builds children before parents (so child ids are always
    // smaller than their parent id). Once every node has a name, the
    // walker's emit-expr structure folds into a sequence of single-op
    // bindings — matching the in-process interpret_v2 trajectory
    // byte-for-byte.
    main_src = main_src + "    // ── bwd materialisation (one binop per let — FMA fence) ──\n"
    let mut bid = fwd_root + 1
    while bid <= bwd_root {
        main_src = main_src + ag_extract_emit_bwd_let(arena, bid, fwd_root)
        bid = bid + 1
    }
    main_src = main_src + "    let dx = _bwd" + to_string(bwd_root) + "\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // json_stringify: shortest-roundtrip codec\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    // (runtime_core.c::_shortest_double) — SD11 lemma.\n"
    main_src = main_src + "    println(json_stringify(dx))\n"
    main_src = main_src + "}\n"
    return bwd_src + main_src
}

// ─── interpret step: bwd AST → numerical evaluation ────────────────────
// `ag_extract_interpret(arena, bwd_root, x_val, dy_val)` — tree-walks
// the bwd AST applying each node's semantics. Produces the same scalar
// value the emitted source WOULD produce if compiled+run. The
// interpret path lets the SD5 oracle compare against a hand-written
// reference INSIDE a single hexa invocation (no second compile cycle).
//
// IEEE-754 byte-eq: each operation here uses the SAME hexa-native
// scalar op a hand-derived bwd would use — `>` for the predicate, the
// upstream `dy` value verbatim, and `0.0` as a literal. The walker
// chooses ONE of the two branches based on the predicate; the
// hand-written reference does the identical branch. Same ops in the
// same order ⇒ identical IEEE-754 last-bit ⇒ max|Δ| = 0.0.
pub fn ag_extract_interpret(arena: int, node: int, x_val: float, dy_val: float) -> float {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        return ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_upstream() {
        return dy_val
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        // SD5 has only one fwd param (x at index 0); future cycles
        // will pass a param vector.
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        if ix == 0 { return x_val }
        return 0.0
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_gt() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let lv = ag_extract_interpret(arena, l, x_val, dy_val)
        let rv = ag_extract_interpret(arena, r, x_val, dy_val)
        if lv > rv { return 1.0 }
        return 0.0
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_ifelse() {
        let c = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let t_br = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let e_br = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 2)
        let cv = ag_extract_interpret(arena, c, x_val, dy_val)
        if cv == 1.0 {
            return ag_extract_interpret(arena, t_br, x_val, dy_val)
        }
        return ag_extract_interpret(arena, e_br, x_val, dy_val)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret(arena, l, x_val, dy_val)
             * ag_extract_interpret(arena, r, x_val, dy_val)
    }
    return 0.0
}

// ─── elementwise driver: apply bwd AST to a vector ─────────────────────
// `ag_extract_relu_bwd_via_ast(arena, bwd_root, x_arr, dy_arr, dx_out,
//  len)` — runs the interpret step over each i ∈ [0, len), writing the
// resulting dx[i] into dx_out. This is the surface the SD5 byte-eq
// oracle compares against the hand-written reference.
pub fn ag_extract_relu_bwd_via_ast(arena: int, bwd_root: int,
                                   x_arr: int, dy_arr: int, dx_out: int,
                                   len: int) {
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len {
        let xi = t_get(x_arr, i)
        let dyi = t_get(dy_arr, i)
        let dxi = ag_extract_interpret(arena, bwd_root, xi, dyi)
        t_set(dx_out, i, dxi)
        i = i + 1
    }
}

// ─── SD6: forward evaluation with cache + interpret v2 ─────────────────
// SD6's interpret path threads a fwd-value cache farr — one cell per
// arena slot. When the walker emits a Var_FwdResult(fid) node, the
// interpret step looks up the cached fwd value at index `fid` rather
// than recomputing the sub-AST. This implements the "save forward,
// reuse in backward" pattern that pure-functional reverse-mode AD
// requires for ops whose vjp uses the output (Call_DTEXP, BinOp_DIV
// in the sigmoid case).
//
// `ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, node, x_val, fwd_cache)` — recursively
// evaluates a fwd-AST node at scalar `x_val`, populating fwd_cache[slot]
// with the result of each visited slot. After a single root-to-leaf
// traversal, the cache contains the fwd value of every fwd-AST node
// reachable from `node`.
pub fn ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena: int, node: int, x_val: float, fwd_cache: int) -> float {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)

    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        let v = if ix == 0 { x_val } else { 0.0 }
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        let v = ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, a, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, b, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let v = va + vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, a, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, b, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let v = va - vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, a, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, b, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let v = va * vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, a, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, b, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let v = va / vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, a, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let v = 0.0 - va
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, a, x_val, fwd_cache)
        let v = dt_exp(va)
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    // Unknown kind in fwd: leave cache untouched, return 0.0.
    return 0.0
}

// `ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, bwd_node, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)` —
// interprets the bwd AST with access to the fwd-value cache. Handles
// the SD6 node-kind extensions (Var_FwdResult, BinOp_ADD/SUB/DIV/NEG,
// Call_DTEXP) in addition to the SD5 kinds.
pub fn ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena: int, node: int,
                                x_val: float, dy_val: float,
                                fwd_cache: int) -> float {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        return ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_upstream() {
        return dy_val
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        if ix == 0 { return x_val }
        return 0.0
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult() {
        let fid = ag_extract_fwdresult_id(arena, node)
        return t_get(fwd_cache, fid)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, l, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             + ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, r, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, l, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             - ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, r, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, l, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             * ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, r, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, l, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             / ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, r, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return 0.0 - ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, l, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let av = ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, l, x_val, dy_val, fwd_cache)
        return dt_exp(av)
    }
    return 0.0
}

// ─── SD6 elementwise driver: sigmoid bwd via AST ───────────────────────
// `ag_extract_sigmoid_bwd_via_ast(arena, fwd_root, bwd_root, x_arr,
//  dy_arr, dx_out, len, fwd_cache)` — for each i ∈ [0, len), evaluates
// the sigmoid fwd at x_arr[i] (populating fwd_cache), then interprets
// the walker-emitted bwd AST against (x, dy, fwd_cache) to produce
// dx_out[i]. This is the surface the SD6 byte-eq oracle compares
// against the hand-written `sigmoid_bwd_manual` reference.
//
// The fwd_cache farr must be sized to the arena capacity (one cell per
// possible slot). It is REUSED across the loop (overwritten each i).
pub fn ag_extract_sigmoid_bwd_via_ast(arena: int, fwd_root: int, bwd_root: int,
                                       x_arr: int, dy_arr: int, dx_out: int,
                                       len: int, fwd_cache: int) {
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len {
        let xi = t_get(x_arr, i)
        let dyi = t_get(dy_arr, i)
        // Populate fwd cache for this x value.
        let _ = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, fwd_root, xi, fwd_cache)
        // Interpret bwd AST against (xi, dyi, fwd_cache).
        let dxi = ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, bwd_root, xi, dyi, fwd_cache)
        t_set(dx_out, i, dxi)
        i = i + 1
    }
}

// ─── SD7: multi-use Param accumulation (foundational autograd primitive) ─
// SD7 closes the "multi-use Param" gap left open by SD6. SD6's walker
// v2 was scoped to fwd graphs where each fwd-intermediate has at most
// one use along the path to the target Param. Sigmoid satisfies that
// (`s = 1/(1+exp(-x))` references x once via `0 − x`). But ANY non-
// trivial elementwise expression — `f(x) = x*x + dt_exp(x)` is the
// canonical multi-use shape — references the SAME target Param more
// than once. The vjp must SUM gradient contributions from every
// usage site (reverse-mode accumulator semantics —
// Griewank & Walther, "Evaluating Derivatives" 2nd ed., §3.2
// "Reverse-Mode Adjoints" Algorithm 3.6, the v̄_i = Σ_j v̄_j · ∂v_j/∂v_i
// accumulation step; Pearlmutter & Siskind §3 lambda-the-ultimate
// vjp transformer also handles multi-use via let-binding's
// compositional reverse-mode rule).
//
// CRITICAL OBSERVATION (foundational): SD6's walker
// `ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2` ALREADY produces the accumulator
// semantics structurally — each `BinOp_*` case recurses into BOTH
// children with their respective derived `dc`, then combines the two
// branches via a fresh `BinOp_ADD`. When the same Param leaf is
// reached along multiple recursion paths, the per-path `dc` is the
// per-usage-site contribution; the ADD nodes at the binop levels are
// where the SUM happens. The Param leaf rule (`return upstream_grad`
// when ix matches) returns the path-local upstream UNTOUCHED — so
// multi-use is the natural recursion shape, not a special case.
//
// SD7 PROVES this by EXERCISING the walker on a 2-use input. No
// walker code changes are required to support multi-use; the
// foundational v_i = Σ_j ... accumulator is already inscribed by the
// SD6 BinOp_*-emits-ADD pattern. What SD7 adds:
//
//   - A new fwd-AST builder for `f(x) = x*x + dt_exp(x)` —
//     `ag_extract_build_multiuse_fwd`. The Param `x` appears 3 times
//     (twice as the two operands of `x*x`, once as the operand of
//     dt_exp). Each occurrence is a SEPARATE fwd-arena Param node so
//     the AST is structurally a tree (each slot has its own fwd_cache
//     entry, written independently by ag_extract_eval_fwd).
//
//   - A new elementwise driver `ag_extract_multiuse_bwd_via_ast` —
//     same shape as ag_extract_sigmoid_bwd_via_ast (fwd-cache populate
//     then bwd-interpret per i), one renaming for the multi-use
//     scenario semantics.
//
//   - A new oracle gate F-RFC043-AUTOGRAD-AUTO-SD7-MULTIUSE-BYTE-EQ
//     (registered in test/flame_ag_extract_test.hexa).
//
// Byte-eq strategy (g3-honest, per task §6 Option A —
// "match the reference's order exactly"):
//
//   The walker's natural emit for `f(x) = (x*x) + dt_exp(x)` walked
//   with upstream = dy and target Param ix = 0, executed top-down,
//   produces this bwd expression (after the per-op rule chain):
//
//     ADD(
//       ADD(                                # MUL(x,x) branch
//         MUL(dy, FwdResult(slot_of_2nd_x)),   # = dy * x  (from da_contrib = dc * b_cached)
//         MUL(dy, FwdResult(slot_of_1st_x))    # = dy * x  (from db_contrib = dc * a_cached)
//       ),
//       MUL(dy, FwdResult(slot_of_dtexp))    # = dy * exp(x) (from Call_DTEXP rule)
//     )
//
//   Evaluated under interpret_v2 with the fwd cache populated, this
//   computes the scalar value
//
//     (((dy * x) + (dy * x)) + (dy * exp_x))
//
//   exactly — same multiplications, same additions, same operand
//   order. The hand-written reference `multiuse_bwd_manual` below
//   computes the SAME expression with the SAME operand sequence
//   (no re-association into `dy * (2*x + exp(x))`), giving
//   IEEE-754 byte-eq (max|Δ| = 0).
//
//   Option A choice: we structure the REFERENCE to mirror the
//   walker's natural emit order, rather than re-associating the
//   walker's output to match the textbook form `dy*(2x+e^x)`. This
//   is the same "match the IEEE-754 trajectory" technique SD5
//   used (its reference computed `if x>0 then dy else 0` via the
//   identical `>` then select). SD6 had to declare byte-eq impossible
//   for sigmoid because the walker emitted `e/d` while the textbook
//   form used `1−s` — algebraic identity, different floating-point
//   trajectory. SD7's multi-use shape does NOT have an algebraic-
//   identity collapse (the walker's emit IS the textbook accumulator
//   form, modulo associativity choice), so Option A is achievable.
//
// What SD7 PROVES (g3-positive deliverables):
//   - The walker handles multi-use Param accumulation CORRECTLY
//     (foundational autograd primitive).
//   - The byte-eq gate PASSES under Option A (reference matches
//     walker order) — proving the multi-use pipeline produces a
//     deterministic, reorder-stable floating-point trajectory.
//   - The "save forward, reuse in backward" cache populates one
//     entry per Param-occurrence slot; cache reads are byte-stable
//     because the same x_val is written to all three slots.
//   - SD1+SD2+SD3+SD5+SD6 regression gates remain green (zero edits
//     to the walker / interpret_v2 / eval_fwd surfaces; only new
//     builder + driver added).
//
// What SD7 does NOT prove (honest carve-outs for SD8+):
//   - Parser integration (SD8 future). The multiuse fwd is
//     hand-built, same idiom as SD5+SD6.
//   - More than one Param (multi-input vjp; SD9 future).
//   - Operator coverage beyond ADD/MUL/dt_exp on the multi-use path
//     (e.g. multi-use through DIV/NEG would exercise the same
//     accumulator machinery but the byte-eq form may differ).
//
// Atlas anchor (g6): Griewank & Walther §3.2 Algorithm 3.6 reverse-
// mode accumulator semantics; Pearlmutter & Siskind §3 compositional
// vjp; same atlas entries SD5/SD6 cite — multi-use is a property of
// the accumulator step, not a new theorem.

// ─── SD7 forward AST builder: f(x) = x*x + dt_exp(x) ───────────────────
// Hand-builds the multi-use fwd AST. The Param `x` appears 3 times,
// each as a SEPARATE fwd-arena Param node (tree, not DAG) so each
// occurrence has its own fwd_cache slot under eval_fwd. The walker
// then visits each occurrence via independent recursion paths and
// the accumulator (the BinOp_ADD that combines the two MUL branches
// + the top-level BinOp_ADD that combines MUL_xx with dt_exp) is
// the sum-of-contributions step.
//
// `cache_out` writes:
//   cache_out[0] = root (the BinOp_ADD at the top)
//   cache_out[1] = mul_xx_node (x*x intermediate)
//   cache_out[2] = exp_x_node  (dt_exp(x) intermediate)
//   cache_out[3] = (reserved 0 — kept for caller farr-shape parity)
//
// Returned: the root slot-id (the top-level ADD).
pub fn ag_extract_build_multiuse_fwd(arena: int, cache_out: int) -> int {
    // Three independent Param(0) nodes — one per occurrence of x in
    // the source `x*x + dt_exp(x)`. Each gets its own arena slot, so
    // eval_fwd populates fwd_cache[slot] = x_val three times (one
    // per slot); the walker's MUL rule reads each via Var_FwdResult.
    let x_node_a = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)   // 1st x in x*x
    let x_node_b = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)   // 2nd x in x*x
    let x_node_c = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)   // x inside dt_exp
    // x*x
    let mul_xx   = ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena, x_node_a, x_node_b)
    // dt_exp(x)
    let exp_x    = ag_extract_mk_call_dtexp(arena, x_node_c)
    // (x*x) + dt_exp(x)
    let root     = ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, mul_xx, exp_x)
    // Publish cache slots.
    t_set(cache_out, 0, to_float(root))
    t_set(cache_out, 1, to_float(mul_xx))
    t_set(cache_out, 2, to_float(exp_x))
    t_set(cache_out, 3, 0.0)
    return root
}

// ─── SD7 elementwise driver: multi-use bwd via AST ─────────────────────
// `ag_extract_multiuse_bwd_via_ast(arena, fwd_root, bwd_root, x_arr,
//  dy_arr, dx_out, len, fwd_cache)` — same shape as sigmoid driver;
// renamed for the multi-use scenario semantics. Per i: populate
// fwd_cache via eval_fwd, then interpret_v2 the bwd-AST root against
// (x, dy, fwd_cache).
pub fn ag_extract_multiuse_bwd_via_ast(arena: int, fwd_root: int, bwd_root: int,
                                        x_arr: int, dy_arr: int, dx_out: int,
                                        len: int, fwd_cache: int) {
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len {
        let xi = t_get(x_arr, i)
        let dyi = t_get(dy_arr, i)
        let _ = ag_extract_eval_fwd(arena, fwd_root, xi, fwd_cache)
        let dxi = ag_extract_interpret_v2(arena, bwd_root, xi, dyi, fwd_cache)
        t_set(dx_out, i, dxi)
        i = i + 1
    }
}

// ─── SD9: multi-input vjp primitive (one VJP per Param) ────────────────
// SD9 closes the "multi-input" carve-out left open by SD7. The walker
// already accepts `target_param_ix` (SD6's `ag_extract_reverse_walk_v2`
// signature); SD5/SD6/SD7 only invoked it with ix=0 because each fwd
// AST had a single Param. SD9 EXERCISES that parameter on a 2-input
// fwd — `f(x, y) = x * y` — by invoking the walker TWICE (once per
// target Param), producing TWO independent bwd ASTs that, when
// interpreted under a 2-slot param-value vector, yield the two
// gradients `df/dx = y` and `df/dy = x` (each scaled by the upstream
// `dy`). This is one column of the Jacobian per call — the literal
// reverse-mode "vector-Jacobian product (VJP)" primitive of Griewank
// & Walther §3.2 Algorithm 3.6: for a scalar output, the VJP IS the
// gradient; for an n-input function, calling the VJP n times (once
// per Param-direction) recovers the full ∇f. Pearlmutter & Siskind
// §3 frames the same as compositional reverse-mode where multiple
// Params are independent leaves of the same recursion tree.
//
// What SD9 adds (additive only; SD5/6/7 surfaces untouched):
//   - `ag_extract_build_bilinear_fwd(arena, cache_out) -> int` —
//     hand-built fwd AST for `f(x, y) = x * y`. Param(0) = x, Param(1)
//     = y; root is a BinOp_MUL. `cache_out[0] = root`, [1] = x_slot,
//     [2] = y_slot, [3] reserved.
//   - `ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, node, param_vals, fwd_cache)`
//     — same shape as `ag_extract_eval_fwd` but reads each Param's
//     scalar from `param_vals[param_ix]` instead of a single `x_val`.
//     Used by the 2-input fwd to populate the cache (x at the x_slot,
//     y at the y_slot, x*y at the root slot).
//   - `ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, node, param_vals, dy_val,
//     fwd_cache)` — same shape as `interpret_v2` but resolves Param
//     leaves against `param_vals` rather than a single `x_val`. Each
//     emitted bwd AST has at most one Var_Upstream (`dy`), so `dy_val`
//     remains scalar — symmetric with SD5/6/7.
//   - `ag_extract_bilinear_bwd_via_ast(arena, fwd_root, bwd_root,
//     x_arr, y_arr, dy_arr, dx_out, len, fwd_cache)` — elementwise
//     driver for ONE Param's gradient. Per i: build a 2-cell
//     param_vals farr [x[i], y[i]], populate fwd_cache via
//     eval_fwd_multi, then interpret the bwd AST via
//     interpret_v2_multi. Same shape is used twice in the test —
//     once with the x-target bwd_root (output goes into dx_out),
//     once with the y-target bwd_root (output goes into dy_out).
//     "Separate per-Param backward functions" (task brief §3 design
//     choice): each invocation returns ONE Param's gradient; calling
//     it n times recovers the full ∇f.
//
// Walker recursion proof (no walker edits needed — same proof shape
// as SD7's multi-use): the walker's Param leaf rule returns
//   if ix == target_param_ix { upstream_grad } else { Const(0.0) }
// For `f(x, y) = x * y` with target_ix = 0:
//   walk(MUL(Param(0), Param(1)), upstream=dy, target=0)
//     ⇒ a_cached = Var_FwdResult(slot_of_Param(0))   = x_cached
//     ⇒ b_cached = Var_FwdResult(slot_of_Param(1))   = y_cached
//     ⇒ dc_b     = MUL(dy, b_cached)                 = MUL(dy, y_cached)
//     ⇒ dc_a     = MUL(dy, a_cached)                 = MUL(dy, x_cached)
//     ⇒ ga       = walk(Param(0), dc_b, target=0)    = dc_b   (ix matches)
//     ⇒ gb       = walk(Param(1), dc_a, target=0)    = Const(0.0)  (ix differs)
//     ⇒ root     = ADD(ga, gb)                       = ADD(MUL(dy, y_cached), Const(0.0))
// Interpret_v2_multi yields `(dy * y) + 0.0` — IEEE-754 byte-equal to
// the textbook `dy * y`? The hand-written reference adopts Option A
// (mirror the walker's emit order verbatim): reference computes
// `t1 = dy * y; t2 = 0.0; dx = t1 + t2` so the trajectory matches.
// Symmetric for target_ix = 1 ⇒ ADD(Const(0.0), MUL(dy, x_cached)),
// reference computes `t1 = 0.0; t2 = dy * x; dy_out = t1 + t2`.
//
// Honest scope (g3):
//   IS  : a minimum-viable 2-Param walker exercise. One call per
//         Param-direction; n calls for n inputs. Scalar upstream;
//         scalar output gradient. Tree fwd AST (no DAG sharing of
//         Param slots — each Param is its own arena node).
//   IS  : verified by byte-eq vs hand-written manual references on a
//         fixed-seed input (len=32) — F-RFC043-AUTOGRAD-AUTO-SD9-
//         BILINEAR-BYTE-EQ. Both `df/dx` and `df/dy` gates measured
//         simultaneously; one PASS verdict requires BOTH gates green.
//   NOT : multi-output (Jacobian column-stack via repeated VJP would
//         be required; SD9 stays scalar-output).
//   NOT : true autograd over a hexa-lang `fn` (parser integration is
//         still SD10's job; the bilinear fwd is hand-built).
//   NOT : a per-Param accumulator dict pass (the alternative design
//         where one walker traversal builds N bwd ASTs simultaneously
//         via a Param→accumulator map). Separate per-Param walker
//         calls is the simpler shape and is what SD9 ships.
//   NOT : matmul / Sum / Compose / arbitrary tensor reductions —
//         still SD10's rule-coverage cycle.
//
// Atlas anchor (g6 — same atlas entries as SD5/6/7; multi-input VJP
// is the literal Algorithm 3.6 specialization to a scalar output):
//   - Griewank & Walther §3.2 Algorithm 3.6: reverse-mode VJP
//     u^T J = grad(u^T f); for u = 1 (scalar output) and
//     target-direction i, the result is ∂f/∂x_i. Calling the
//     algorithm once per i ∈ [0, n) recovers ∇f.
//   - Pearlmutter & Siskind §3: each Param is an independent leaf of
//     the recursion; the per-Param-index leaf rule (return upstream
//     if matching, Const(0.0) otherwise) is the compositional
//     identity for multi-input vjp.

// ─── SD9 forward AST builder: f(x, y) = x * y ──────────────────────────
// Hand-builds the bilinear fwd AST. Two distinct Param indices (0 and
// 1), both wired into a single BinOp_MUL. Returns the root MUL slot.
//
// `cache_out` writes (mirror SD7 convention for caller introspection):
//   cache_out[0] = root  (the MUL node — the f output)
//   cache_out[1] = x_node (Param(0) slot)
//   cache_out[2] = y_node (Param(1) slot)
//   cache_out[3] = 0      (reserved)
pub fn ag_extract_build_bilinear_fwd(arena: int, cache_out: int) -> int {
    let x_node = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)   // f's first param
    let y_node = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 1)   // f's second param
    let root   = ag_extract_mk_binop_mul(arena, x_node, y_node)
    t_set(cache_out, 0, to_float(root))
    t_set(cache_out, 1, to_float(x_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 2, to_float(y_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 3, 0.0)
    return root
}

// ─── SD9 fwd eval with param-vals vector ───────────────────────────────
// `ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, node, param_vals, fwd_cache)` —
// same shape as `ag_extract_eval_fwd` but resolves each Param leaf
// against `param_vals[param_ix]` rather than a single x_val. Mirrors
// every op branch of eval_fwd verbatim (so identical IEEE-754
// trajectory for any single-Param sub-AST when param_vals[0] == x_val).
pub fn ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena: int, node: int, param_vals: int, fwd_cache: int) -> float {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)

    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        let v = t_get(param_vals, ix)
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        let v = ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, a, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, b, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let v = va + vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, a, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, b, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let v = va - vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, a, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, b, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let v = va * vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let b = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, a, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let vb = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, b, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let v = va / vb
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, a, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let v = 0.0 - va
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let a = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let va = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, a, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        let v = dt_exp(va)
        t_set(fwd_cache, node, v)
        return v
    }
    return 0.0
}

// ─── SD9 bwd interpret with param-vals vector ──────────────────────────
// `ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, node, param_vals, dy_val,
//  fwd_cache)` — same shape as `interpret_v2` but resolves Param
// leaves against the `param_vals` farr rather than a single x_val.
// The upstream `dy_val` remains scalar (each emitted bwd AST has a
// single Var_Upstream leaf — symmetric across all prior SDs).
pub fn ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena: int, node: int,
                                      param_vals: int, dy_val: float,
                                      fwd_cache: int) -> float {
    let k = ag_extract_kind(arena, node)
    if k == ag_extract_k_const() {
        return ag_extract_const_value(arena, node)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_upstream() {
        return dy_val
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_param() {
        let ix = ag_extract_param_ix(arena, node)
        return t_get(param_vals, ix)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_var_fwdresult() {
        let fid = ag_extract_fwdresult_id(arena, node)
        return t_get(fwd_cache, fid)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_add() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, l, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             + ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, r, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_sub() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, l, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             - ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, r, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_mul() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, l, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             * ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, r, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_div() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let r = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 1)
        return ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, l, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
             / ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, r, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_binop_neg() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        return 0.0 - ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, l, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
    }
    if k == ag_extract_k_call_dtexp() {
        let l = ag_extract_child(arena, node, 0)
        let av = ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, l, param_vals, dy_val, fwd_cache)
        return dt_exp(av)
    }
    return 0.0
}

// ─── SD9 elementwise driver: bilinear bwd via AST (one Param dir) ──────
// `ag_extract_bilinear_bwd_via_ast(arena, fwd_root, bwd_root, x_arr,
//  y_arr, dy_arr, d_out, len, fwd_cache, param_vals)` — runs the
// 2-input fwd + 1-Param bwd elementwise. `bwd_root` is a per-Param
// bwd AST (produced by calling reverse_walk_v2 with target_param_ix
// = 0 for the df/dx direction, or 1 for df/dy); `d_out` receives the
// chosen Param's gradient. The caller supplies a reusable 2-cell
// `param_vals` farr (overwritten each i: [x[i], y[i]]).
//
// Calling this twice (once per per-Param bwd_root) gets both
// gradients — the "separate per-Param backward functions" shape
// from task brief §3.
pub fn ag_extract_bilinear_bwd_via_ast(arena: int, fwd_root: int, bwd_root: int,
                                        x_arr: int, y_arr: int, dy_arr: int,
                                        d_out: int, len: int,
                                        fwd_cache: int, param_vals: int) {
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len {
        let xi  = t_get(x_arr, i)
        let yi  = t_get(y_arr, i)
        let dyi = t_get(dy_arr, i)
        // Populate param_vals farr for this i.
        t_set(param_vals, 0, xi)
        t_set(param_vals, 1, yi)
        // Populate fwd_cache by evaluating fwd at (x_i, y_i).
        let _ = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, fwd_root, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        // Interpret bwd AST against (param_vals, dy_i, fwd_cache).
        let d_i = ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, bwd_root, param_vals, dyi, fwd_cache)
        t_set(d_out, i, d_i)
        i = i + 1
    }
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// SD10 — multi-input arithmetic vjp (SD6 ULP zone × SD9 multi-input)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// SD10 closes the "multi-input arithmetic" gap by composing SD6's per-op
// rules (DIV / NEG / ADD / dt_exp) with SD9's multi-input target_ix
// machinery. Test function: `f(x, y) = x / (1 + dt_exp(0 − y))`. This is
// the sigmoid-weighted scalar division — `f = x · s(y)` algebraically
// where `s(y) = 1/(1+exp(-y))`, but the source shape uses DIV at the
// root rather than MUL, so the walker emits a structurally different
// bwd than SD9's bilinear MUL.
//
// Mathematical gradients (the answer the walker is checked against):
//
//   df/dx = 1 / (1 + exp(-y)) = s(y)
//   df/dy = x · s(y) · (1 − s(y))         (sigmoid-derivative reappears
//                                           — the SD6 ULP zone)
//
// SD10 exercises the cross-product of SD6 and SD9 — multi-input AND
// arithmetic-ladder rules in the same fwd. Two new properties get
// tested that SD9 (pure MUL) did not stress:
//   (i)  DIV at the root of a multi-input fwd: the walker's DIV rule
//        threads `da_local = upstream / b_cached` and `db_local =
//        NEG(upstream × c_cached / b_cached_2)` — for target=x, only
//        `ga = walk(Param(0), da_local, 0)` is non-zero and reduces to
//        `dy / d`. The reference, following the task brief's "SD6's
//        exact form, use 1-s", computes `dy × s` where
//        `s = 1.0 / d` is recomputed in the manual.
//        Walker emits `dy / d` (one DIV); reference emits
//        `dy × (1.0 / d)` (DIV + MUL). Different IEEE-754 trajectory ⇒
//        df/dx is expected to be HONEST 1-ULP (or possibly byte-eq
//        when rounding accidentally aligns; the test reports the
//        verdict honestly without preselecting which).
//   (ii) DIV + NEG + dt_exp recursion under target=y: only the
//        sigmoid-of-y subtree is non-zero; the walker emits a long
//        chain `NEG(MUL(db_local, e_cached))` where
//        `db_local = NEG(DIV(MUL(dy, c_cached), d_cached_2))` —
//        nesting THREE algebraic-identity opportunities. Reference
//        uses SD6's `dy × x × s × (1 − s)` form (recomputes s and
//        1−s manually). Same SD6 reorder lesson under multi-input —
//        HONEST 1-ULP zone expected. Both ways of writing the
//        gradient are mathematically equal:
//        `dy × c × e / d  =  dy × (x/d) × e / d  =  dy × x × s × (e/d)
//        =  dy × x × s × (1 − s)`.
//
// What SD10 PROVES: the SD6 walker's per-op rule table composes
// faithfully with SD9's target_ix indirection. No walker edits needed.
// The HONEST 1-ULP outcome (where it occurs) confirms that SD6's
// reorder-lesson generalizes to the multi-input case — multi-input
// does not magically erase IEEE-754 last-bit divergence; it preserves
// it edge-for-edge. The PASS outcome (where the algebraic shape
// happens to align with the walker emit) confirms that some
// composed-arithmetic shapes are exactly byte-equal even under
// multi-input.
//
// What SD10 does NOT prove (g3 honest carve-outs):
//   - Multi-output Jacobian column-stack (still a scalar-output fwd).
//   - Parser integration (SD8 stays out-of-scope; hand-built fwd).
//   - Single-pass per-Param accumulator dict (still SD12; SD10 calls
//     the walker twice, once per Param direction, the SD9 idiom).
//   - Sum / MatMul / Compose / silu-gelu-tanh rule coverage — those
//     are now SD13 (renumbered from the SD9-era "SD10" carve-out;
//     this cycle re-uses the SD10 slot per task brief).
//
// Atlas anchors (g6 — same set as SD5/6/7/9 plus SD6's reorder note):
//   - Griewank & Walther §3.2 Algorithm 3.6 — reverse-mode VJP, here
//     specialized to two Params + DIV-rooted fwd. The per-direction
//     call recovers one Jacobian column at a time.
//   - Griewank & Walther §3.2 elementary-primitives table — DIV rule
//     `da = dc/b · db = -dc·c/b` and dt_exp rule `da = dc · c_cached`.
//   - SD6 reorder note (this file's SD6 header) — algebraic-identity
//     ULP divergence: walker's `e/d` and reference's `1 − s` are
//     mathematically equal but differ in last-bit rounding; the same
//     divergence appears in SD10 under multi-input.
//   - Pearlmutter & Siskind §3 — compositional vjp; each Param is an
//     independent leaf, target-ix selects which Param direction.
//
// ─── SD10 forward AST builder: f(x, y) = x / (1 + dt_exp(0 − y)) ───────
// Hand-builds the SD10 fwd AST. Two distinct Param indices (0=x,
// 1=y); root is BinOp_DIV whose denominator is the SD6 sigmoid
// shape `1 + dt_exp(0 − y)` (without the outer `1/(…)` — that's the
// `d_node` slot, and we let the OUTER DIV produce `x / d` directly).
//
// `cache_out` writes (mirror SD9 convention for caller introspection):
//   cache_out[0] = root_node (the DIV — the f output)
//   cache_out[1] = x_node    (Param(0))
//   cache_out[2] = y_node    (Param(1))
//   cache_out[3] = d_node    (the denominator 1 + dt_exp(0 − y))
//
// Slot count: 8 fwd nodes (x, y, zero_a, u=zero_a-y, e=dt_exp(u),
// one_a, d=one_a+e, root=DIV(x,d)). Leaves headroom for ~17 bwd
// nodes per Param direction (full DIV/NEG/dt_exp recursion), so two
// per-Param walks under the 64-slot capacity (sized 8 + 17 + 17 = 42).
pub fn ag_extract_build_sigmoid_div_multi_fwd(arena: int, cache_out: int) -> int {
    // x (param index 0) — numerator
    let x_node       = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 0)
    // y (param index 1) — input to sigmoid-shaped denominator
    let y_node       = ag_extract_mk_param(arena, 1)
    // 0.0 (literal — used in `0 − y`, mirrors SD6's NEG-via-SUB shape)
    let zero_node_a  = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 0.0)
    // u = 0.0 − y (the input negation; reserved BinOp_NEG kind stays
    // for future unary-prefix syntax — SD6 convention)
    let u_node       = ag_extract_mk_binop_sub(arena, zero_node_a, y_node)
    // e = dt_exp(u)
    let e_node       = ag_extract_mk_call_dtexp(arena, u_node)
    // 1.0 (literal — denominator's leading constant)
    let one_node_a   = ag_extract_mk_const(arena, 1.0)
    // d = 1.0 + e
    let d_node       = ag_extract_mk_binop_add(arena, one_node_a, e_node)
    // root = x / d  (the f output — same shape an honest parser would
    // emit for `pub fn f(x, y) = x / (1.0 + dt_exp(0.0 − y))`)
    let root         = ag_extract_mk_binop_div(arena, x_node, d_node)
    t_set(cache_out, 0, to_float(root))
    t_set(cache_out, 1, to_float(x_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 2, to_float(y_node))
    t_set(cache_out, 3, to_float(d_node))
    return root
}

// ─── SD10 elementwise driver: sigmoid-div multi bwd via AST ────────────
// `ag_extract_sigmoid_div_multi_bwd_via_ast(arena, fwd_root, bwd_root,
//  x_arr, y_arr, dy_arr, d_out, len, fwd_cache, param_vals)` — runs the
// 2-input fwd + 1-Param bwd elementwise. Symmetric to SD9's
// `ag_extract_bilinear_bwd_via_ast` (identical signature) — called
// twice in the SD10 test (once with the x-target bwd_root, once with
// the y-target bwd_root). Mechanically identical to SD9's driver; we
// add a thin SD10-named alias for self-documenting call sites.
//
// (We could call SD9's `ag_extract_bilinear_bwd_via_ast` directly —
// the param_vals + fwd_cache + interpret_v2_multi machinery is
// op-agnostic — but the named wrapper makes the test's two paths
// (SD9 bilinear vs SD10 sigmoid-div) trivially greppable.)
pub fn ag_extract_sigmoid_div_multi_bwd_via_ast(arena: int,
                                                  fwd_root: int, bwd_root: int,
                                                  x_arr: int, y_arr: int, dy_arr: int,
                                                  d_out: int, len: int,
                                                  fwd_cache: int, param_vals: int) {
    let mut i = 0
    while i < len {
        let xi  = t_get(x_arr, i)
        let yi  = t_get(y_arr, i)
        let dyi = t_get(dy_arr, i)
        // Populate param_vals farr for this i.
        t_set(param_vals, 0, xi)
        t_set(param_vals, 1, yi)
        // Populate fwd_cache by evaluating fwd at (x_i, y_i).
        let _ = ag_extract_eval_fwd_multi(arena, fwd_root, param_vals, fwd_cache)
        // Interpret bwd AST against (param_vals, dy_i, fwd_cache).
        let d_i = ag_extract_interpret_v2_multi(arena, bwd_root, param_vals, dyi, fwd_cache)
        t_set(d_out, i, d_i)
        i = i + 1
    }
}

// ─── Future work (g3 carve-outs) ───────────────────────────────────────
//
// SD5 established the AST→walk→emit pipeline shape for ONE op (relu).
// SD6 demonstrated GENERALIZATION to a SECOND op (sigmoid) via the
// per-op rule table (ADD/SUB/MUL/DIV/NEG/dt_exp) + Var_FwdResult cache.
// SD7 demonstrated MULTI-USE Param gradient accumulation
// — the foundational autograd primitive — on `f(x) = x*x + dt_exp(x)`.
// What SD7 PROVED: the walker's existing recursion structure (each
// BinOp emits ADD combining its two child contributions) IS the
// accumulator; no walker edits needed. Reference matches walker order
// (Option A) so byte-eq holds. SD7 also proved the foundational point
// that ANY non-trivial expression (with reused vars) flows through
// this accumulator path — without it, no real-world model would work.
// SD9 demonstrated MULTI-INPUT VJP — calling the walker once per
// target Param recovers ∇f for `f(x, y) = x * y`. The foundational
// claim: the `target_param_ix` parameter already in the walker's
// signature suffices for n-input vjp; no walker edits needed.
// SD10 (this cycle) demonstrated MULTI-INPUT ARITHMETIC VJP — SD6's
// per-op rule table composed with SD9's target_ix indirection on
// `f(x, y) = x / (1 + dt_exp(0 − y))`. The DIV at the root, the
// `0 − y` SUB inside the dt_exp, and the multi-input target ix
// machinery all compose with zero walker edits; the byte-eq verdict
// per Param direction is reported honestly (SD6's algebraic-identity
// ULP zone applies under multi-input — last-bit divergence is not
// erased by the multi-input mechanism).
//
// To extend to true source-to-source AD over arbitrary hexa-lang
// functions, the following structural blockers remain (each its own SD):
//
//   SD8 — parser integration. The compiler/parse/ast.hexa Module/
//         Item/Expr types are available, but importing them into a
//         stdlib file pulls in compiler/lex + compiler/parse + diag,
//         which would expand stdlib/flame's transitive dep
//         significantly. The right cycle is to expose a thin
//         `parse_function_body(path, fn_name) -> Expr` surface that
//         strips the parser-internal state.
//
//   SD11 — re-emit-and-recompile loop. The SD6 emit step produces a
//          hexa source string referencing _fwd<id> cached values.
//          A future cycle wires the emitted source through the
//          compiler so it is actually loaded and called (closing
//          the source-to-source loop).
//
//   SD12 — single-pass multi-input via per-Param accumulator dict.
//          SD9 uses the simpler "n walker calls, one per Param"
//          shape. An alternative is one walker traversal that
//          maintains a Param→accumulator map, building all n bwd
//          ASTs simultaneously. Equivalent VJP semantics; cheaper
//          when n is large. Honest carve-out: not needed for the
//          near-term flame use case (n ≤ a few hundred Params per
//          layer; n walker calls suffices).
//
//   SD13 — more reverse-mode rules (renumbered from the SD9-era
//          "SD10" slot). SD5/6/9/10 cover ADD/SUB/MUL/DIV/NEG +
//          dt_exp + IfElse. Generic vjp coverage still needs Sum
//          (reduce-axis), MatMul (transpose × upstream — SD1's body,
//          AST-derived this time), Compose (let-binding chain rule),
//          and the elementwise unary family (silu, gelu, tanh — each
//          adds one rule, all citation-anchored in Griewank–Walther
//          Tables 4.1–4.3).
//
// Each future SD has its own falsifier registered before work
// starts (per the scoping note §4 "each SD has its own falsifier
// registered in FLAME.tape").
//
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
